04467nam a22007215i 9780801455582DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20152014nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)1000438102  a97808014555827 a10.7591/97808014555822doi  a(DE-B1597)478295  a(OCoLC)979740830  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aDF229.T6bN53 2016 7aHIS0020102bisacsh04a938.050922231 aNichols, Mary P., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aThucydides and the Pursuit of Freedom /cMary P. Nichols. 1aIthaca, NY : bCornell University Press, c[2015] 4c©2014  a1 online resource (208 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- t1. Periclean Athens and an Image of Freedom -- t2. Athenian Freedom in the Balance: Mytilene and Plataea -- t3. Sparta, Brasidas, and the Liberation of Hellas -- t4. Sicily, Alcibiades, and the Liberation of Erōs -- t5. Homecoming and Freedom -- tConclusion -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn Thucydides and the Pursuit of Freedom, Mary P. Nichols argues for the centrality of the idea of freedom in Thucydides' thought. Through her close reading of his History of the Peloponnesian War, she explores the manifestations of this theme. Cities and individuals in Thucydides' history take freedom as their goal, whether they claim to possess it and want to maintain it or whether they desire to attain it for themselves or others. Freedom is the goal of both antagonists in the Peloponnesian War, Sparta and Athens, although in different ways. One of the fullest expressions of freedom can be seen in the rhetoric of Thucydides’ Pericles, especially in his famous funeral oration. More than simply documenting the struggle for freedom, however, Thucydides himself is taking freedom as his cause. On the one hand, he demonstrates that freedom makes possible human excellence, including courage, self-restraint, deliberation, and judgment, which support freedom in turn. On the other hand, the pursuit of freedom, in one’s own regime and in the world at large, clashes with interests and material necessity, and indeed the very passions required for its support. Thucydides’ work, which he himself considered a possession for all time, therefore speaks very much to our time, encouraging the defense of freedom while warning of the limits and dangers in doing so. The powerful must defend freedom, Thucydides teaches, but beware that the cost not become freedom itself.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aLiberty. 4aAncient History & Classical Studies. 4aHistory. 4aPhilosophy. 7aHISTORY / Ancient / Greece.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311060674408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2017z978311066587140uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/978080145558240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780801455582423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780801455582.jpg  a978-3-11-060674-4  Cornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  a978-3-11-066587-1  Cornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2017b2017  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_CL  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_CL  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK